I like the builder pattern here, it is better than constructors with various params. Can we directly use the builder to build the service itself instead of building the interim config object? Here are the differences of these two apis:

What the PR uses:


```
// on server
    ClusterManagementServiceConfig config = GeodeClusterManagementServiceConfig.builder()
        .setCache(ClusterStartupRule.getCache())
        .setUserName()
        .setPassword()
        .build();
    ClusterManagementService service = new ClientClusterManagementService(config);

    // on geode client  -- can't set username/password first before setting the cache
    ClusterManagementServiceConfig config = GeodeClusterManagementServiceConfig.builder()
        .setClientCache(ClusterStartupRule.getClientCache())
        .setUsername()
        .setPassword()
        .build();
    ClusterManagementService service = new ClientClusterManagementService(config);


    // on java client
    ClusterManagementServiceConfig config = JavaClientClusterManagementServiceConfig.builder()
        .setHost("localhost")
        .setPort(locator.getHttpPort())
        .setUsername("test")
        .setPassword("test")
        .build();
    cmsClient = new ClientClusterManagementService(config);
 ```
  
Suggested API:

```
// on server
    ClusterManagementService service = new GeodeManagementServiceBuilder().setCache(cache).setUserName().setPassword().build();
    
    // on geode client
    ClusterManagementService service = new GeodeManagementServiceBuilder().setClientCache(cache).setUserName().setPassword().build();
    
    // on java client
     ClusterManagementService service = new JavaClientManagementServiceBuilder().setHost(host).setPort(port).setUsername().setPassword().build();```

Then how about:
```
// on server
    ClusterManagementService service = ClusterManagementServiceBuilder.builder().setCache(cache).setUserName().setPassword().build();
    
    // on geode client
    ClusterManagementService service = ClusterManagementServiceBuilder.builder().setClientCache(cache).setUserName().setPassword().build();
    
    // on java client
     ClusterManagementService service =ClusterManagementServiceBuilder.builder().setHost(host).setPort(port).setUsername().setPassword().build();```

```
the first two `builder()` returns a `GeodeClientBuilder` while the last one returns a `JavaClientBuilder` depending on which one is available in the jar. Just a thought, not sure if it's doable or not.

With this, the compiler is still happy when we do this
```
RegionConfig regionConfig = new RegionConfig();
List<MemberConfig> result = service.list(regionConfig, MemberConfig.class).getResult();
```

We can avoid overly "genetify" the interface simply by adding a getResult(Class) method in ClusterManagementResult:
```
  public <R extends RuntimeCacheElement> List<R> getResult(Class<R> clazz) {
    return result.stream().map(clazz::cast).collect(Collectors.toList());
  }
```

